  "doc_id": "20428",
  "text": "It is clear that the first method cannot approximate the real-world continuous surface well. To improve the accuracy of DTMs, a large number of studies have focused on DTM construction for interpolations, such as IDW, SPLINE [CITATION_1] , KRIGING [CITATION_2] , optimization methods based on theorems of surfaces [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , fractal methods [CITATION_5] , and the Coons path method [CITATION_6] . These interpolators can be constructed based on a quadrangular irregular network similar to the regular grid model because of their common topological structure. In this paper, we fit a polynomial surface to the irregular quadrilateral using bicubic interpolation, which preserves fine details better than common algorithms do. And an inter-comparison is drawn among this integral QIN method, other two interpolation methods (SPLINE and KRIGING) and TIN method, to analyse the simulation accuracy.",
